    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>120800</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>67.1495</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cherstich2009"/>, fig. <citedRange>107</citedRange></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2020c"/>, p. <citedRange>318-319</citedRange>, n. 7 and fig. 7</bibl>;
            <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.37</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Πρατομήδης">Πρατομήδης</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Φίλιππος">Φιλίππω</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratomèdès fils de Philippos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratomedes son of Philippos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pratomedes figlio di Philippos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>The findspot is a tomb surveyed by Cherstich in 2007 and not previously registered by Cassels, in the South necropolis.</p>
               <p>With this base, we now know the burial place of a man of high rank: commander of cavalry about 345 BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr084000</ref>, l. 13), 
                   he is mentioned both as ephoros and nomothetes in the <foreign rend="italic">diagramma</foreign> of Ptolemy in 320 (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr010800</ref>, ll. 83 and 86).
                    He may have died at the latest about 300 BC, but probably nearer to 320 BC.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
